Hi Cesar,

Wanted to share an important finding from our investigation today that directly addresses your skepticism about the ~1M certificate entries.

You were right to question whether these were organic. They were not.

Root cause identified:

We traced the entire bloat to 8 abandoned CentOS 6 café/lab machines in our SJC office. These machines were stuck in a certmonger renewal spiral caused by an IPA permissions issue — certmonger was getting 'Insufficient write privilege' to the userCertificate attribute and rather than giving up, it retried indefinitely.

The numbers:
- 857,722 VALID certificates in ou=certificateRepository belonged to just 8 hosts (~107,000 certs each)
- Those same 8 hosts generated the bulk of the completed certificate requests
- Every other host in the environment has 3-24 certs which is completely normal
- The spiral was being proxied through sjc-ipareplica01 (192.168.99.34)

Actions taken:
- Stopped certmonger on all 8 machines
- Shut down the machines — they are abandoned CentOS 6 EOL systems with no active users
- Currently running a bulk LDAP delete of the 857,722 certificates from ou=certificateRepository,ou=ca,o=ipaca
- Will follow up with cleanup of the associated completed certificate requests

Once cleanup is complete we will proceed with the clean fresh install of pln-ipamaster as recommended.

We will also be enabling the cert pruning feature on pln-ipamaster (IPA 4.12 / RHEL 9) on day one to prevent this from recurring.

Thanks again for pushing us to investigate — this was exactly the right call.

Best regards,
